explanation:
Why each symbol is required to decide whether OS_CondVarTimedWait contains dead code:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER
  - This macro (or inline check) appears in the target function and can change control flow (e.g. log, return an error, abort, or be a no-op). To determine if the check or any code it expands to is dead (removable without changing observable behaviour), the exact expansion and any side effects must be known.

- OS_printf
  - OS_CHECK_POINTER or other parameter checks commonly call logging routines such as OS_printf. Logging has observable side effects; whether those calls are meaningful (and thus not dead) depends on the implementation of OS_printf. Knowing its behaviour (no-op, conditional on runtime flags, or performing I/O) is needed to decide if removing logging would alter program behaviour.

- OS_ObjectIdGetById
  - The result of this call controls the conditional that invokes OS_CondVarTimedWait_Impl. To know whether the 'if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS) { ... }' body can ever be executed (and thus whether it is dead), the implementation and possible return codes/side effects of OS_ObjectIdGetById must be inspected. Also, OS_ObjectIdGetById may itself have side effects (state changes, transactions) that are relevant to dead-code analysis.

- OS_CondVarTimedWait_Impl
  - This is the function conditionally called. Determining whether that call is removable requires knowing whether the implementation produces observable behaviour (e.g., blocking, changing global state, signaling, timing effects). If it has side effects or timing effects, the call is not dead.

- OS_SUCCESS
  - The literal/enum used in the conditional must be identified so the comparison is interpreted correctly. Understanding all possible return values and their meanings is necessary to determine reachability and whether the conditional body is effectively dead.

- OS_INVALID_POINTER
  - Parameter-check macros often return a specific error code on null pointers. To reason whether the OS_CHECK_POINTER expands to an early return (which would make subsequent code unreachable in that path) or only logs, the actual error code(s) it uses must be known. Including the typical invalid-pointer return constant (or whatever concrete error code/symbol the project uses) lets the analyzer determine observable effects of the check.

Notes: The above set is minimal to decide whether any executed operations in OS_CondVarTimedWait are removable without changing observable behaviour. If deeper investigation of OS_ObjectIdGetById is needed, its internal helpers (e.g., OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit, OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex, OS_ObjectIdConvertToken, OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel) may also be required, but start with the symbols listed above.
